        "header": "3ZipSplat: Decoupling Gaussians from the Pixel Grid",
        "images": [
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2606.05102/2606.05102v1/x2.png",
                "caption": "Figure 2:Overview of ZipSplat.GivenNNinput images, a multi-view backbone extracts dense visual tokens, which are compressed via k-means clustering intoKKscene tokens.\nCross- and self-attention layers refine the scene tokens by attending back to the full visual tokens, and a lightweight MLP decodes each token intoGGGaussians with unconstrained 3D positions.\nThe compression ratiorris adjustable at inference, giving a single model a continuous quality-efficiency knob.",
                "position": 441
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2606.05102/2606.05102v1/x3.png",
                "caption": "Figure 3:Pixel-alignedvs.token-based Gaussian placement.For each method we show a novel-view rendering (left) and the Gaussian centers (right).\nYoNoSplat (a) distributes centers uniformly across the views, mirroring the 2D pixel grid regardless of scene content.\nZipSplat (b) places Gaussians freely in 3D, concentrating them on geometrically detailed regions while allocating fewer to flat surfaces like walls and floors.",
                "position": 469
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2606.05102/2606.05102v1/x4.png",
                "caption": "",
                "position": 472
